The following passage describes a runtime weight precision swap mechanism for on-device large language model inference. Read it carefully and continue the explanation. The key insight is that during a precision swap, weights of individual layers are replaced atomically while decoding continues, and the choice of how many layers to swap per decode step controls the latency profile observed by the user. Specifically, as more layer swaps are performed over time (or in a single request), latencies increase linearly with 10-32% per swap.

The swapping mechanism is implemented in two ways: on-device and off-device.
